om-ish names, which when &#8220;also aggregate inline CSS&#8221; is active makes the AO cache grow incredibly fast. As a workaround you can add .wp-container- to the CSS optimization exclusions. I have just pushed out Autoptimize 2.9.5.1 which automatically ... <a title=\"Autoptimize &#038; WordPress 5.9 issue with aggregated inline CSS\" class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://blog.futtta.be/2022/01/26/autoptimize-wordpress-5-9-issue-with-aggregated-inline-css/\" aria-label=\"More on Autoptimize &#038; WordPress 5.9 issue with aggregated inline CSS\">Read more</a>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"futtta\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:517:\"<p>WordPress 5.9 comes with a change I had not noticed before; it is adding inline CSS with random-ish names, which when &ldquo;also aggregate inline CSS&rdquo; is active makes the AO cache grow incredibly fast. As a workaround you can add to the CSS optimization exclusions. I have just pushed out Autoptimize 2.9.5.1 which automatically excludes inline CSS with that string.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://blog.futtta.be/2022/01/26/autoptimize-wordpress-5-9-issue-with-aggregated-inline-css/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Source</a></p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:98:\"https://blog.futtta.be/2022/01/26/autoptimize-wordpress-5-9-issue-with-aggregated-inline-css/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8: